Note:
IPV6 ADDRESS - 128-bit IPv6 Address Primitive (Tier 1)

Implements the IPv6Address value type per RFC 4291 (IP Version 6 Addressing
Architecture) and RFC 8200 (Internet Protocol, Version 6 Specification).

Representation:
  An IPv6 address is 128 bits, stored as two 64-bit limbs (high, low) in a
  16-byte allocated record. Limb byte ordering treats the high limb as the
  most-significant 64 bits in canonical "X:X:X:X:X:X:X:X" reading order.

  Record layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0: high_limb (most-significant 64 bits)
    offset 8: low_limb  (least-significant 64 bits)

Canonical text form follows RFC 5952:
  - All-lowercase hexadecimal digits.
  - Suppress leading zeros within each group.
  - Compress the single longest run of all-zero groups using "::".
  - If multiple equal-length zero runs exist, compress the first.
  - Do not compress a single zero group; "::" must replace two or more.

Classification predicates implemented (per RFC 4291 / RFC 8190):
  - is_loopback        ::1                                 RFC 4291 2.5.3
  - is_unspecified     ::                                  RFC 4291 2.5.2
  - is_link_local      fe80::/10                           RFC 4291 2.5.6
  - is_multicast       ff00::/8                            RFC 4291 2.7
  - is_unique_local    fc00::/7                            RFC 4193
  - is_ipv4_mapped     ::ffff:0:0/96                       RFC 4291 2.5.5.2
  - is_ipv4_compatible ::w.x.y.z/96 (deprecated form)      RFC 4291 2.5.5.1
  - is_global          remainder, after exclusions

CIDR range is implemented as a 24-byte record holding two limb words for
the base address plus an 8-byte prefix length 0..128.

Implementation notes:
  - All arithmetic operates on Runa Integer (64-bit signed), so each limb
    is intentionally kept within the 0..2^63 - 1 positive range when used
    as a bit-pattern. The high bit of each limb is encoded distinctly via
    a separate sign flag is not required because individual 16-bit group
    values are always positive (0..65535) when reading from the address.

  - Group extraction uses fixed shifts implemented via repeated halving and
    masking to remain compatible with the bootstrap arithmetic surface.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/string_builder.runa" as SB
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let IPV6_BYTES be 16
Let IPV6_BITS be 128
Let IPV6_GROUPS be 8
Let IPV6_GROUP_BITS be 16
Let IPV6_GROUP_MAX be 65535
Let IPV6_RECORD_SIZE be 16
Let IPV6_RANGE_SIZE be 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Build an IPv6 address from eight 16-bit groups in canonical
left-to-right order (group 0 is the most-significant group). The result is
a freshly allocated 16-byte record. Caller owns the memory and must free it
via ipv6_destroy. Returns 0 on validation failure or allocation failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Validate every group in 0..65535. Pack the first four groups into the
high_limb (each group shifted into its 16-bit slot via multiplication by
the appropriate power of two) and the last four groups into low_limb.

  high_limb = (g0 * 2^48) + (g1 * 2^32) + (g2 * 2^16) + g3
  low_limb  = (g4 * 2^48) + (g5 * 2^32) + (g6 * 2^16) + g7
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - exactly 16 bytes per address. Eight bounds checks
plus constant-time arithmetic.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Group bounds checked before packing so callers cannot inject a value with
spurious high bits that would alter classification predicates downstream.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_from_segments" takes g0 as Integer, g1 as Integer, g2 as Integer, g3 as Integer, g4 as Integer, g5 as Integer, g6 as Integer, g7 as Integer returns Integer:
    If g0 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g0 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g1 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g1 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g2 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g2 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g3 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g3 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g4 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g4 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g5 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g5 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g6 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g6 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g7 is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g7 is greater than IPV6_GROUP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let high_part_0 be g0 multiplied by 281474976710656
    Let high_part_1 be g1 multiplied by 4294967296
    Let high_part_2 be g2 multiplied by 65536
    Let high_limb be high_part_0 plus high_part_1
    Set high_limb to high_limb plus high_part_2
    Set high_limb to high_limb plus g3

    Let low_part_0 be g4 multiplied by 281474976710656
    Let low_part_1 be g5 multiplied by 4294967296
    Let low_part_2 be g6 multiplied by 65536
    Let low_limb be low_part_0 plus low_part_1
    Set low_limb to low_limb plus low_part_2
    Set low_limb to low_limb plus g7

    Let addr be proc allocate from Layout with IPV6_RECORD_SIZE
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, high_limb
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 8, low_limb
    Return addr
End Process

@Reasoning
Build an IPv6 address from a 16-byte buffer in network byte order (the wire
representation: most-significant byte first, matching the order specified
in RFC 4291 section 2.2).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read each of 16 bytes from the buffer and pack two consecutive bytes into
each 16-bit group. Then call ipv6_from_segments which performs bounds
validation and limb packing.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) over 16 fixed bytes. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Validates the input pointer is non-null. The 16-byte read assumes the
caller has provided a valid buffer of at least 16 bytes; this is a
documented precondition per RFC 4291.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_from_bytes_16" takes buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 0
    Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 1
    Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 2
    Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 3
    Let b4 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 4
    Let b5 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 5
    Let b6 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 6
    Let b7 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 7
    Let b8 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 8
    Let b9 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 9
    Let b10 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 10
    Let b11 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 11
    Let b12 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 12
    Let b13 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 13
    Let b14 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 14
    Let b15 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with buffer, 15

    Let g0 be (b0 multiplied by 256) plus b1
    Let g1 be (b2 multiplied by 256) plus b3
    Let g2 be (b4 multiplied by 256) plus b5
    Let g3 be (b6 multiplied by 256) plus b7
    Let g4 be (b8 multiplied by 256) plus b9
    Let g5 be (b10 multiplied by 256) plus b11
    Let g6 be (b12 multiplied by 256) plus b13
    Let g7 be (b14 multiplied by 256) plus b15

    Return proc ipv6_from_segments with g0, g1, g2, g3, g4, g5, g6, g7
End Process

@Reasoning
Free an IPv6 address record. Mirror of construction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegates to the layout deallocator.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must not touch pointer after destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_destroy" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with addr
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Extract a single 16-bit group (0..7) from the address. Group 0 corresponds
to the most-significant 16 bits and is the leftmost field in canonical
notation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Groups 0..3 live in high_limb at slots 48, 32, 16, 0 (bit offsets).
Groups 4..7 live in low_limb  at slots 48, 32, 16, 0 (bit offsets).
For group i in the high limb at bit-slot s, the value is:
  (high_limb / 2^s) modulo 65536
Same for the low limb.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1). One division, one modulus.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on out-of-range index so callers can distinguish error from a
legitimate 0 group.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_get_segment" takes addr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If index is greater than 7:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If index is equal to 0:
        Return (high_limb divided by 281474976710656) modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 1:
        Return (high_limb divided by 4294967296) modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 2:
        Return (high_limb divided by 65536) modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 3:
        Return high_limb modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 4:
        Return (low_limb divided by 281474976710656) modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 5:
        Return (low_limb divided by 4294967296) modulo by 65536
    End If
    If index is equal to 6:
        Return (low_limb divided by 65536) modulo by 65536
    End If
    Return low_limb modulo by 65536
End Process

@Reasoning
Render the 16-byte network-order wire representation. Each group becomes
two bytes (high, low). Caller owns returned 16-byte buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For each group i in 0..7 extract g_i and write bytes
  buffer[2i]   = g_i divided by 256
  buffer[2i+1] = g_i modulo 256
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) over 8 fixed groups. Space: O(1) for the 16-byte output.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_to_bytes_16" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 16
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let g be proc ipv6_get_segment with addr, i
        Let high_byte be g divided by 256
        Let low_byte be g modulo by 256
        Let base_offset be i multiplied by 2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, base_offset, high_byte
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buffer, base_offset plus 1, low_byte
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HEX DIGIT HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Convert a single ASCII hex digit to its integer value 0..15. Accepts both
upper and lower case per RFC 5952 (canonical output is lowercase but input
is liberal).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range tests on '0'..'9', 'a'..'f', 'A'..'F'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on invalid digit so callers can detect malformed input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_hex_value" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return ch minus 48
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return ch minus 87
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return ch minus 55
        End If
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning
Convert an integer 0..15 to its lowercase ASCII hex digit per RFC 5952
which mandates lowercase output for canonical text representation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
0..9 -> '0'..'9', 10..15 -> 'a'..'f'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on out-of-range input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_hex_digit_char" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than 15:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is less than 10:
        Return value plus 48
    End If
    Return value plus 87
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARSING (RFC 4291 textual representation)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Parse a textual IPv6 address per RFC 4291 section 2.2. Supports:
  - Full eight-group form "1:2:3:4:5:6:7:8"
  - "::" compression of one or more zero groups (only one "::" allowed)
  - Mixed IPv4-mapped form is not handled here; callers requiring "x:x:x:x:x:x:d.d.d.d"
    should use a dedicated entry point. Plain colon-hex form is RFC-compliant
    and covers the overwhelming majority of real-world addresses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Two-pass strategy:
  Pass 1: scan to count actual groups, detect "::" position, validate digit set.
  Pass 2: emit groups, inserting zero-fill for the compressed gap.

The compression position is determined by counting groups before the "::"
(left side) and inferring the gap size as 8 - (left_count + right_count).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over string length, n <= 39 in practice. Space: O(1) plus 16
bytes for the resulting address record.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict validation: empty input, double "::" beyond the single allowed
compression, non-hex characters, > 4 digits per group, > 8 total groups,
gap inferred as <= 0 all return 0. No partial state escapes the parser.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_from_string" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than 39:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate scratch storage for up to 8 groups, plus tracking state.
    Note: Layout: groups[0..7] as int64 (64 bytes), gap_position (8 bytes), gap_present (8 bytes), groups_before_gap (8 bytes), groups_after_gap (8 bytes) - total 96 bytes.
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 96
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let g_index be 0
    While g_index is less than 12:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with scratch, g_index multiplied by 8, 0
        Set g_index to g_index plus 1
    End While

    Let current_group be 0
    Let digits_in_group be 0
    Let groups_total be 0
    Let gap_present be 0
    Let groups_before_gap be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let parse_failed be 0

    While i is less than length:
        If parse_failed is equal to 1:
            Set i to length
        Otherwise:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i
            If ch is equal to 58:
                Note: colon. Check for double-colon.
                Let next_i be i plus 1
                Let is_double be 0
                If next_i is less than length:
                    Let next_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, next_i
                    If next_ch is equal to 58:
                        Set is_double to 1
                    End If
                End If
                If is_double is equal to 1:
                    If gap_present is equal to 1:
                        Set parse_failed to 1
                    Otherwise:
                        If digits_in_group is greater than 0:
                            If groups_total is greater than 7:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            Otherwise:
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with scratch, groups_total multiplied by 8, current_group
                                Set groups_total to groups_total plus 1
                                Set current_group to 0
                                Set digits_in_group to 0
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set gap_present to 1
                        Set groups_before_gap to groups_total
                        Set i to i plus 1
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    If digits_in_group is equal to 0:
                        Set parse_failed to 1
                    Otherwise:
                        If groups_total is greater than 7:
                            Set parse_failed to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with scratch, groups_total multiplied by 8, current_group
                            Set groups_total to groups_total plus 1
                            Set current_group to 0
                            Set digits_in_group to 0
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Let hv be proc ipv6_hex_value with ch
                If hv is less than 0:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set current_group to current_group multiplied by 16
                    Set current_group to current_group plus hv
                    Set digits_in_group to digits_in_group plus 1
                    If digits_in_group is greater than 4:
                        Set parse_failed to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Commit trailing group if any pending digits.
    If digits_in_group is greater than 0:
        If groups_total is greater than 7:
            proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with scratch, groups_total multiplied by 8, current_group
        Set groups_total to groups_total plus 1
    End If

    Note: Final validation: must have exactly 8 groups, or compression must fill gap.
    Let final_groups be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If final_groups is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
        Return 0
    End If
    Let f be 0
    While f is less than 8:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with final_groups, f multiplied by 8, 0
        Set f to f plus 1
    End While

    If gap_present is equal to 1:
        Let groups_after_gap be groups_total minus groups_before_gap
        Let gap_size be 8 minus groups_total
        If gap_size is less than 1:
            proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
            proc deallocate from Layout with final_groups
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: Copy pre-gap groups.
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than groups_before_gap:
            Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with scratch, k multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with final_groups, k multiplied by 8, val
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Note: Copy post-gap groups, shifted right by gap_size.
        Let m be 0
        While m is less than groups_after_gap:
            Let src_index be groups_before_gap plus m
            Let dst_index be groups_before_gap plus gap_size plus m
            Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with scratch, src_index multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with final_groups, dst_index multiplied by 8, val
            Set m to m plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        If groups_total is not equal to 8:
            proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
            proc deallocate from Layout with final_groups
            Return 0
        End If
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than 8:
            Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with scratch, k multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with final_groups, k multiplied by 8, val
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let g0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 0
    Let g1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 8
    Let g2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 16
    Let g3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 24
    Let g4 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 32
    Let g5 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 40
    Let g6 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 48
    Let g7 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with final_groups, 56
    proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    proc deallocate from Layout with final_groups

    Return proc ipv6_from_segments with g0, g1, g2, g3, g4, g5, g6, g7
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CANONICAL FORMATTING (RFC 5952)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Render canonical text form per RFC 5952. The longest run of zero groups
is compressed using "::". If multiple equal-length runs exist, the first
(leftmost) is chosen. A single zero group is never compressed (RFC 5952
section 4.2.2). Output is lowercase hex with leading zeros suppressed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Extract all 8 groups.
2. Scan for the longest run of zero groups of length >= 2. Tie-break by
   choosing the leftmost (first) run, per RFC 5952 section 4.2.3.
3. Emit groups, replacing the chosen run with "::". Single zero groups
   outside the compression are emitted as "0".
4. Use a StringBuilder to assemble the output; finalize to a string.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) over 8 fixed groups. Space: O(1) - output bounded by ~39 chars.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Output only; no untrusted input parsed. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_to_string" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract 8 groups into a scratch buffer.
    Let groups_buf be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If groups_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let g be proc ipv6_get_segment with addr, i
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with groups_buf, i multiplied by 8, g
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Find longest run of zero groups (length >= 2).
    Let best_start be -1
    Let best_length be 0
    Let cur_start be -1
    Let cur_length be 0
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with groups_buf, i multiplied by 8
        If val is equal to 0:
            If cur_start is equal to -1:
                Set cur_start to i
                Set cur_length to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set cur_length to cur_length plus 1
            End If
            If cur_length is greater than best_length:
                Set best_start to cur_start
                Set best_length to cur_length
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set cur_start to -1
            Set cur_length to 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If best_length is less than 2:
        Set best_start to -1
        Set best_length to 0
    End If

    Note: Emit groups, replacing the run with "::".
    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with groups_buf
        Return 0
    End If

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let at_run_start be 0
        If best_start is equal to i:
            Set at_run_start to 1
        End If
        If at_run_start is equal to 1:
            If i is equal to 0:
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 58
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 58
            Otherwise:
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 58
            End If
            Set i to i plus best_length
        Otherwise:
            Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with groups_buf, i multiplied by 8
            Let nibble3 be (val divided by 4096) modulo by 16
            Let nibble2 be (val divided by 256) modulo by 16
            Let nibble1 be (val divided by 16) modulo by 16
            Let nibble0 be val modulo by 16
            Let emitted_any be 0
            If nibble3 is greater than 0:
                Let c3 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble3
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c3
                Set emitted_any to 1
            End If
            If emitted_any is equal to 1:
                Let c2 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble2
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c2
            Otherwise:
                If nibble2 is greater than 0:
                    Let c2 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble2
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c2
                    Set emitted_any to 1
                End If
            End If
            If emitted_any is equal to 1:
                Let c1 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble1
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c1
            Otherwise:
                If nibble1 is greater than 0:
                    Let c1 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble1
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c1
                    Set emitted_any to 1
                End If
            End If
            Let c0 be proc ipv6_hex_digit_char with nibble0
            proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, c0
            Set i to i plus 1
            If i is less than 8:
                proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 58
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    proc deallocate from Layout with groups_buf
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The unspecified address "::" (all zeros) per RFC 4291 section 2.5.2.
Indicates the absence of an address; never appears as a destination.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Both limbs zero.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Drop unspecified destinations at the input filter.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_unspecified" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If high_limb is equal to 0:
        If low_limb is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Loopback "::1" per RFC 4291 section 2.5.3. Must never appear on a real
link interface.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
high_limb == 0 and low_limb == 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Reject loopback in ingress firewalls.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_loopback" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If high_limb is equal to 0:
        If low_limb is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Link-local prefix fe80::/10 per RFC 4291 section 2.5.6. Auto-configured
on every IPv6 interface; never routed beyond the link.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Top 10 bits equal 0xFE80 >> 6 = 0x3FA. The first 16-bit group has the
form 1111 1110 10xx xxxx, so g0 in [0xfe80, 0xfebf].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Routers must not forward link-local addresses.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_link_local" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let g0 be proc ipv6_get_segment with addr, 0
    If g0 is less than 65152:
        Return 0
    End If
    If g0 is greater than 65215:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Multicast prefix ff00::/8 per RFC 4291 section 2.7. The first byte equals
0xFF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Group 0's high byte equals 0xFF, i.e. g0 / 256 == 255.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Multicast dispatch differs from unicast routing.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_multicast" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let g0 be proc ipv6_get_segment with addr, 0
    Let high_byte be g0 divided by 256
    If high_byte is equal to 255:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Unique-Local Address (ULA) prefix fc00::/7 per RFC 4193. Locally-assigned
but globally unique with high probability; not routed publicly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
First 7 bits equal 1111110. So g0 high byte in [0xFC, 0xFD].
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Should not appear on the public Internet.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_unique_local" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let g0 be proc ipv6_get_segment with addr, 0
    Let high_byte be g0 divided by 256
    If high_byte is equal to 252:
        Return 1
    End If
    If high_byte is equal to 253:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
IPv4-mapped address ::ffff:0:0/96 per RFC 4291 section 2.5.5.2. Used to
represent IPv4 traffic inside an IPv6 socket API.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
high_limb == 0 and (low_limb / 2^32) == 0xFFFF.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Required for dual-stack socket handling.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_ipv4_mapped" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If high_limb is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    Let prefix_word be low_limb divided by 4294967296
    If prefix_word is equal to 65535:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
IPv4-compatible address ::w.x.y.z/96 per RFC 4291 section 2.5.5.1. This
form is deprecated but still recognized for legacy interop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
high_limb == 0 and (low_limb / 2^32) == 0 and the embedded IPv4 portion
is non-zero and is not the IPv4-mapped sentinel.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Modern deployments reject this form per current best practice (RFC 4291
section 2.5.5.1 deprecation note).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_ipv4_compatible" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If high_limb is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    Let prefix_word be low_limb divided by 4294967296
    If prefix_word is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ipv4_part be low_limb modulo by 4294967296
    If ipv4_part is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ipv4_part is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Test for global unicast addressability: anything that is not unspecified,
loopback, link-local, multicast, unique-local, IPv4-mapped, or IPv4-compatible.
This corresponds to addresses delegated through the regional registries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Logical AND-NOT across the special-purpose predicates.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Use for egress validation of "real" Internet traffic.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_is_global" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let un be proc ipv6_is_unspecified with addr
    If un is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lb be proc ipv6_is_loopback with addr
    If lb is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ll be proc ipv6_is_link_local with addr
    If ll is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mc be proc ipv6_is_multicast with addr
    If mc is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ul be proc ipv6_is_unique_local with addr
    If ul is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let im be proc ipv6_is_ipv4_mapped with addr
    If im is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ic be proc ipv6_is_ipv4_compatible with addr
    If ic is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IPV4 INTEROP
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Wrap an IPv4 address in the IPv4-mapped IPv6 form ::ffff:a.b.c.d per
RFC 4291 section 2.5.5.2. Used by dual-stack sockets to present IPv4
peers through the IPv6 API.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
high_limb = 0
low_limb  = (0xFFFF << 32) | ipv4_value
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must validate ipv4 value is in 0..2^32 - 1.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_ipv4_mapped_in_ipv6" takes ipv4_value as Integer returns Integer:
    If ipv4_value is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ipv4_value is greater than 4294967295:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let low_prefix be 65535 multiplied by 4294967296
    Let low_limb be low_prefix plus ipv4_value
    Let addr be proc allocate from Layout with IPV6_RECORD_SIZE
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 8, low_limb
    Return addr
End Process

@Reasoning
Extract the embedded IPv4 address from an IPv4-mapped IPv6 address. Per
RFC 4291 the IPv4 value occupies the low 32 bits of an address whose
upper 96 bits are 0:0:0:0:0:ffff.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Verify is_ipv4_mapped. Return low_limb modulo 2^32.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 if the address is not actually an IPv4-mapped address so the
caller never accidentally extracts a value from a global IPv6 address.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_ipv4_from_mapped" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let is_mapped be proc ipv6_is_ipv4_mapped with addr
    If is_mapped is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    Return low_limb modulo by 4294967296
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CIDR RANGE - IPv6Range
Note: ============================================================================

Note: IPv6Range layout (24 bytes):
Note:   offset 0:  base_high (8 bytes)
Note:   offset 8:  base_low  (8 bytes)
Note:   offset 16: prefix_len (8 bytes - 0..128)

@Reasoning
Create an IPv6Range from a base address and prefix length per RFC 4291
section 2.3. The base address is canonicalized (host bits zeroed) at
construction time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Validate prefix in 0..128. Canonicalize via per-limb masking driven by
the prefix length crossing the 64-bit boundary.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1) - 24 bytes per range.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Canonicalization prevents equivalent prefixes from differing in storage.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_range_create" takes base_addr as Integer, prefix_len as Integer returns Integer:
    If base_addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If prefix_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If prefix_len is greater than IPV6_BITS:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let high_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with base_addr, 0
    Let low_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with base_addr, 8

    Note: Canonicalize: zero host bits.
    If prefix_len is less than 64:
        Note: Mask high limb to prefix_len bits, zero low limb entirely.
        Let host_bits be 64 minus prefix_len
        Let high_chunk be 1
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than host_bits:
            Set high_chunk to high_chunk multiplied by 2
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Let canonical_high be high_limb divided by high_chunk
        Set canonical_high to canonical_high multiplied by high_chunk
        Set high_limb to canonical_high
        Set low_limb to 0
    Otherwise:
        If prefix_len is less than 128:
            Let host_bits be 128 minus prefix_len
            Let low_chunk be 1
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than host_bits:
                Set low_chunk to low_chunk multiplied by 2
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
            Let canonical_low be low_limb divided by low_chunk
            Set canonical_low to canonical_low multiplied by low_chunk
            Set low_limb to canonical_low
        End If
    End If

    Let range be proc allocate from Layout with IPV6_RANGE_SIZE
    If range is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with range, 0, high_limb
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with range, 8, low_limb
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with range, 16, prefix_len
    Return range
End Process

@Reasoning
Free an IPv6Range record.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Layout deallocator.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must not touch pointer after destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_range_destroy" takes range as Integer returns Integer:
    If range is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with range
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Parse a CIDR string of the form "ipv6_text/prefix" per RFC 4291 section 2.3.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Locate '/'. Split into address and prefix. Parse via ipv6_from_string and
decimal scan respectively. Construct via ipv6_range_create. Caller takes
ownership of the resulting range; intermediate address record is freed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(1) plus the resulting 24-byte range.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Rejects malformed input; never returns a partially-initialized range.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_range_from_cidr_string" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    If length is less than 4:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slash_pos be -1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i
        If ch is equal to 47:
            Set slash_pos to i
            Set i to length
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    If slash_pos is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If slash_pos is greater than or equal to length minus 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let addr_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with str, 0, slash_pos
    If addr_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let prefix_start be slash_pos plus 1
    Let prefix_len_chars be length minus prefix_start
    Let prefix_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with str, prefix_start, prefix_len_chars
    If prefix_str is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with addr_str
        Return 0
    End If

    Let addr be proc ipv6_from_string with addr_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with addr_str
    If addr is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with prefix_str
        Return 0
    End If

    Let prefix_value be 0
    Let pj be 0
    Let prefix_chars be proc string_length from StringCore with prefix_str
    If prefix_chars is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with prefix_str
        proc ipv6_destroy with addr
        Return 0
    End If
    If prefix_chars is greater than 3:
        proc deallocate from Layout with prefix_str
        proc ipv6_destroy with addr
        Return 0
    End If
    Let prefix_failed be 0
    While pj is less than prefix_chars:
        Let pc be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with prefix_str, pj
        Let is_d be proc is_digit from Char with pc
        If is_d is equal to 0:
            Set prefix_failed to 1
            Set pj to prefix_chars
        Otherwise:
            Set prefix_value to prefix_value multiplied by 10
            Set prefix_value to prefix_value plus (pc minus 48)
            Set pj to pj plus 1
        End If
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with prefix_str
    If prefix_failed is equal to 1:
        proc ipv6_destroy with addr
        Return 0
    End If
    If prefix_value is greater than IPV6_BITS:
        proc ipv6_destroy with addr
        Return 0
    End If
    Let range be proc ipv6_range_create with addr, prefix_value
    proc ipv6_destroy with addr
    Return range
End Process

@Reasoning
Test if an address falls within the CIDR range. Membership is defined by
the canonical base address matching the address masked to the prefix.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Compute masked(addr) using the range's prefix and compare to base.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) over fixed limbs. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on null input or mismatched address.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "ipv6_range_contains_address" takes range as Integer, addr as Integer returns Integer:
    If range is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If addr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let base_high be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with range, 0
    Let base_low be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with range, 8
    Let prefix_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with range, 16
    Let addr_high be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    Let addr_low be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8

    Let masked_high be addr_high
    Let masked_low be addr_low
    If prefix_len is less than 64:
        Let host_bits be 64 minus prefix_len
        Let high_chunk be 1
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than host_bits:
            Set high_chunk to high_chunk multiplied by 2
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Let trimmed_high be addr_high divided by high_chunk
        Set masked_high to trimmed_high multiplied by high_chunk
        Set masked_low to 0
    Otherwise:
        If prefix_len is less than 128:
            Let host_bits be 128 minus prefix_len
            Let low_chunk be 1
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than host_bits:
                Set low_chunk to low_chunk multiplied by 2
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
            Let trimmed_low be addr_low divided by low_chunk
            Set masked_low to trimmed_low multiplied by low_chunk
        End If
    End If

    If masked_high is equal to base_high:
        If masked_low is equal to base_low:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process
